{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἑρπετόν</b>, <br /> <i>Aeolic dialect</i> perhaps <b>ὄρπετον</b> (which see), τό, (ἕρπω) <b>beast</b> or <b>animal which goes on all fours,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.418; πᾶν ἑ. πληγῇ νέμεται 1st c.AD(?): Heraclitus 11; ἑρπετὰ ὅσσα τρέφει μέλαινα γαῖα 7th c.BC: Alcman Lyricus 60.3; ὄφις καὶ σαύρας καὶ τὰ τοιαῦτα τῶν ἑρπετῶν 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.183; τοῖς μὲν ἄλλοις ἑρπετοῖς πόδας ἔδωκεν.., ἀνθρώπῳ δὲ καὶ χεῖρας 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 1.4.11 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἑρπετά, opposed to πετεινά, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.140, compare 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 15.118, 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 4.1240: generally, ἑ. οὐδὲ γυνή 3rd c.BC: Callimachus Epicus “Hymnus in Jovem” 13 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πυκινώτατον ἑ., of a hound, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 106 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of insects, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC(?): Semonides Iambographus 13, 2nd c.BC: Nicander Epicus “fragment” 74.46. \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>creeping thing, reptile,</b> especially <b>snake,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 269, 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 24.57; περὶ κιναδέων τε καὶ ἑ. 3rd c.AD: Democritus Epigrammaticus 259; ἑρπετά τε καὶ δάκετα [πάντα] 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 1069 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of the monster Typhoeus, with a <b>snake's</b> body, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.25. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> as <i>adjective</i>, <b>creeping,</b> κακὸν ἑ. πρᾶγμα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “POxy.” 1060.7 (6th c.AD)\">Refs 6th c.AD+</a>]; τὰ ἑ. θηρία [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Philumenus